In the morning, Emily decided to create some designs with her cereal bits. In total, she created 9 designs and used 63 cereal bits. About how many cereal bits were in each design? Do you think she used an equal number of cereal bits in each design?
To find the average amount of cereal bits used per design, we need to first divide the total number of cereal bits by the number of designs. 
So, 63 cereal bits used / 9 designs = 7.11 (rounded to two decimal places) cereal bits per design.
To determine if she used an equal amount of cereal bits in each design, we can compare this value to the range of possible values. Since we don't know how many designs were larger or smaller than the others, we will assume that all 9 designs had the same number of cereal bits.
If we assume that Emily used an equal amount of cereal bits in each design, then the range of possible values for the average amount of cereal bits per design would be from 0 to 7.11 (inclusive). However, since it is not possible for all designs to have only 0 or 7.11 cereal bits, we can conclude that Emily did not use an equal amount of cereal bits in each design.
